And as a child, I was just
taught to treasure what the

01:04:44.967 --> 01:04:48.367
Earth gives us and to make sure
that we leave it for

01:04:48.367 --> 01:04:50.266
the next generation.

01:04:50.266 --> 01:04:53.734
And obviously in a
country like South Africa,

01:04:53.734 --> 01:04:58.500
with incredible beauty
and natural resources,

01:04:58.500 --> 01:05:03.200
that same mentality about
conserving the Earth and

01:05:03.200 --> 01:05:06.867
nurturing it to pass on to
future generations, I think,

01:05:06.867 --> 01:05:12.000
applies here just as much as
it does in the United States.

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:15.467
The biggest challenge we have
environmentally -- and it is an

01:05:15.467 --> 01:05:19.633
international challenge that we
cannot solve alone --

01:05:19.633 --> 01:05:21.967
is the issue of climate change.

01:05:21.967 --> 01:05:27.734
There are other issues:
dirty water, dirty air.

01:05:27.734 --> 01:05:32.300
But the truth is, is that we've
made enormous progress over the

01:05:32.300 --> 01:05:35.133
last several years, over the
last several decades

01:05:35.133 --> 01:05:36.567
in the United States.

01:05:36.567 --> 01:05:38.834
And if you come to
the United States,

01:05:38.834 --> 01:05:41.367
environmental quality
is pretty good.

01:05:41.367 --> 01:05:48.367
And internationally, we've
promoted policies around how

01:05:48.367 --> 01:05:53.467
mercury is released
into the environment,

01:05:53.467 --> 01:05:56.600
and how other poisons are
released in the environment,

01:05:56.600 --> 01:05:59.767
and how businesses have to be
held to international standards

01:05:59.767 --> 01:06:02.800
in terms of worker safety.

01:06:02.800 --> 01:06:05.000
Those are areas where the
United States have been

01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:05.967
at the forefront.

01:06:05.967 --> 01:06:07.700
We've been at the
front of the line,

01:06:07.700 --> 01:06:10.333
not the back of the line when
it comes to those issues.

01:06:10.333 --> 01:06:16.233
But the existential challenge
that we face has to do with

01:06:16.233 --> 01:06:18.467
a warming planet.

01:06:18.467 --> 01:06:20.700
And your generation is the one
that's going to be

01:06:20.700 --> 01:06:24.000
the most severely affected.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:30.000
Now, the United States and
other highly industrialized,

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:33.800
developed countries
over the last 50,

01:06:33.800 --> 01:06:37.834
100 years have been pumping
up carbon emissions

01:06:37.834 --> 01:06:40.000
into the atmosphere.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:44.133
And slowly, this has been
building up and it is warming

01:06:44.133 --> 01:06:49.900
the planet, and we may be
reaching a tipping point

01:06:49.900 --> 01:06:55.533
in which if we do not
solve this problem soon,

01:06:55.533 --> 01:06:58.033
it will spin out of control and
change weather patterns in ways

01:06:58.033 --> 01:07:01.934
that we can't anticipate,
with drought, floods,

01:07:01.934 --> 01:07:06.834
much more severe
natural disasters.

01:07:06.834 --> 01:07:09.400
And unfortunately, in those
situations it's often poorer

01:07:09.400 --> 01:07:13.600
countries that are affected the
most by these changing

01:07:13.600 --> 01:07:16.100
climate patterns.

01:07:16.100 --> 01:07:21.066
So I just gave a speech this
past week on what the United

01:07:21.066 --> 01:07:23.967
States is going to do on our
next phase of reducing

01:07:23.967 --> 01:07:25.266
our carbon emissions.

01:07:25.266 --> 01:07:27.200
The United States actually
reduced our carbon emissions

01:07:27.200 --> 01:07:33.367
more than any other country
since I came into office.

01:07:33.367 --> 01:07:34.233
I just want to make that point.

01:07:34.233 --> 01:07:37.467
(applause)

01:07:37.467 --> 01:07:39.200
We doubled
fuel-efficiency

01:07:39.200 --> 01:07:40.433
standards on cars.

01:07:40.433 --> 01:07:44.400
We're investing in clean
energy like solar and wind.

01:07:44.400 --> 01:07:47.667
And we actually want to
share that technology,

01:07:47.667 --> 01:07:51.567
because we think that all
countries need to benefit.

01:07:51.567 --> 01:07:54.600
And part of the opportunity
for Africa is to see if we can

01:07:54.600 --> 01:08:03.033
leapfrog some of the polluting
practices of America or Europe,

01:08:03.033 --> 01:08:07.467
and go straight to the clean
energy strategies that will

01:08:07.467 --> 01:08:13.033
allow you to advance
economic growth,

01:08:13.033 --> 01:08:16.066
but not corrupt the planet.

01:08:16.066 --> 01:08:20.367
So we've made progress,
but we haven't done enough.

01:08:20.367 --> 01:08:23.967
And what I did was to say I
challenge the United States.

01:08:23.967 --> 01:08:26.166
I said we've got to do more.

01:08:26.166 --> 01:08:27.934
We're going to start regulating
our power plants

01:08:27.934 --> 01:08:29.667
more efficiently.

01:08:29.667 --> 01:08:33.967
We're going to make sure that we
redouble our efforts to reduce

01:08:33.967 --> 01:08:37.567
our carbon emissions, and we're
setting a goal to meet the

01:08:37.567 --> 01:08:42.100
agreements that we had both in
Copenhagen and in Durban for

01:08:42.100 --> 01:08:46.633
advanced countries that
have a big carbon footprint.

01:08:46.633 --> 01:08:50.433
But let me make one last point:
The United States cannot

01:08:50.433 --> 01:08:53.934
do it by itself.

01:08:53.934 --> 01:09:01.233
And the biggest emitter of
carbon right now is China.

01:09:01.233 --> 01:09:05.767
They still have a much lower
carbon footprint per person than

01:09:05.767 --> 01:09:11.033
the United States, but because
they have so many people,

01:09:11.033 --> 01:09:12.800
it's going up rapidly.

01:09:12.800 --> 01:09:16.467
And Chinese leaders
understand this.

01:09:16.467 --> 01:09:18.166
The same thing that's sending
all the carbon into the

01:09:18.166 --> 01:09:23.333
atmosphere is also making it
difficult to breathe in Beijing.

01:09:23.333 --> 01:09:24.900
So they recognize they've got to
come up with

01:09:24.900 --> 01:09:26.834
a new development model.

01:09:26.834 --> 01:09:29.233
India is going to have to come
up with new development

01:09:29.233 --> 01:09:32.066
models -- Africa.

01:09:32.066 --> 01:09:37.834
We're going to all have to work
together to find ways in which

01:09:37.834 --> 01:09:43.200
collectively, we reduce carbon
but we make sure that there's

01:09:43.200 --> 01:09:48.934
some differentiation so that
countries that are very wealthy

01:09:48.934 --> 01:09:53.867
are expected to do more, and
countries that are still

01:09:53.867 --> 01:09:58.533
developing, obviously they
shouldn't be resigned to poverty

01:09:58.533 --> 01:10:04.266
simply because the West and
Europe and America

01:10:04.266 --> 01:10:06.633
got there first.

01:10:06.633 --> 01:10:07.567
That wouldn't be fair.

01:10:07.567 --> 01:10:11.066
But everybody is going
to have to do something.

01:10:11.066 --> 01:10:12.600
Everybody is going to have to
make some

01:10:12.600 --> 01:10:15.166
important choices here.

01:10:15.166 --> 01:10:18.567
And I expect that it's going to
be your generation that helps

01:10:18.567 --> 01:10:21.500
lead this, because if we don't,
it's going to be your generation

01:10:21.500 --> 01:10:25.033
that suffers the most.

01:10:25.033 --> 01:10:27.700
Ultimately, if you think about
all the youth that everybody has

01:10:27.700 --> 01:10:30.967
mentioned here in Africa, if
everybody is raising living

01:10:30.967 --> 01:10:33.367
standards to the point where
everybody has got a car

01:10:33.367 --> 01:10:35.166
and everybody has got
air conditioning,

01:10:35.166 --> 01:10:38.467
and everybody has got
a big house, well,

01:10:38.467 --> 01:10:42.133
the planet will boil over --
unless we find new ways of

01:10:42.133 --> 01:10:43.300
producing energy.

01:10:43.300 --> 01:10:47.834
And tomorrow, or the next
day, when I visit Tanzania,

01:10:47.834 --> 01:10:50.300
I'm actually going to be going
to a power plant to focus on the

01:10:50.300 --> 01:10:52.734
need for electrification,
but the need to do it

01:10:52.734 --> 01:10:56.533
in an environmentally sound way.

01:10:56.533 --> 01:10:59.500
So let me just close by saying
this has been

01:10:59.500 --> 01:11:03.800
an unbelievable conversation.

01:11:03.800 --> 01:11:06.233
I had a lot of faith in all
of you before I came here;

01:11:06.233 --> 01:11:09.166
now I have even
more faith in you.

01:11:09.166 --> 01:11:10.834
You guys are all going
to do great things.

01:11:10.834 --> 01:11:15.967
I'll be retired by
the time you do them,

01:11:15.967 --> 01:11:18.600
and so I'll just sit back and
watch -- (laughter) -- and I'll

01:11:18.600 --> 01:11:20.200
be proud of you.

01:11:20.200 --> 01:11:24.767
But what I promise you is that
the United States government and

01:11:24.767 --> 01:11:29.600
the American people are going to
want to be your partner for the

01:11:29.600 --> 01:11:31.066
duration of your careers.

01:11:31.066 --> 01:11:33.734
And I hope all of you, again,
apply for

01:11:33.734 --> 01:11:38.133
the Young African Leaders Initiative.

01:11:38.133 --> 01:11:43.000
We want to hear from you about
how we can work even more

01:11:43.000 --> 01:11:45.066
effectively with
this great continent,

01:11:45.066 --> 01:11:48.300
because we see a
bright future ahead.

01:11:48.300 --> 01:11:49.467
I hope you've enjoyed it.

01:11:49.467 --> 01:11:50.066
Thank you, everybody.

01:11:50.066 --> 01:11:51.967
God bless you.

01:11:51.967 --> 01:11:53.066
Thank you.

01:11:53.066 --> 01:11:56.300
(applause)

